definition.value: Crop residue that have been dried

label.value: obsolete concentration of carbon dioxide in soil

value.value: obsolete A role that inheres in a material entity that is mined from mineral deposits or manufactured from synthetic compounds and that excludes carbon-containing materials except ureas.
Fence established by planting large cuttings, that easily produce roots and on which several strings of wire are attached with the obvious purpose of keeping livestock in or out.

http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI.value: "Harvey, C.A., Villanueva, C., Villacís, J., Chacón, M., Muñoz, D., López, M., Ibrahim, M., Gómez, R., Taylor, R., Martinez, J. and Navas, A., 2005. Contribution of live fences to the ecological integrity of agricultural landscapes. Agriculture, ecosystems & environment, 111(1-4), pp.200-230. ecological integrity of agricultural landscapes"

value.value: Live fence made of trees. Boundary planting are used to delimitate property, agricultural fields, pastures, roads or any other place where fences might be located.

http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI.value: Baker, K., Baumann, D., Michaud, J.S., van Mossel-Forrester, B., 2014. Technical Specification Boundary Planting. Registered Plan Vivo Project: The CommuniTree Carbon Project. 64p. URL: https://takingroot.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/takingroot-boundary-planting.pdf

value.value: Windbreaks are linear plantings of trees and shrubs designed to enhance crop production, protect people and livestock, and benefit soil and water conservation.
Multiple row windbreaks that are planted for both production of tree crops and environmental benefits like wind protection, soil conservation, wildlife habitat.
Fence where one or more rows of trees and/or shrubs are specifically planted to provide a visual screen or intercept light, odour, dust, and noise or a combination thereof.
Tree plantings which are grown in hedgerows but have been allowed to reach their full height and width.
Fodder collected to provide cattle farmers with high quality fodder for the dry season.

http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI.value: BRENCHLEY, W. The Management of Farm Woodlands. Nature 146, 475 (1940). https://doi.org/10.1038/146475a0

value.value: Trees which have ecological functions in landscapes like offering shelter and food sources for animals, enhancing landscape connectivity by acting as stepping stones, and functioning as nuclei for plant regeneration in disturbed landscapes.

definition.value: Scattered trees may enhance the provision of ecosystem services that might benefit farmers and owners of rural properties, such as pollination of crops, shading for cattle, regulation of nitrogen dynamics and carbon sequestration, herbaceous production, and wood provision.

value.value: An agroforestry process where peasant farmers are permitted to seed crops between trees during the establishment phase of plantation forestry.

http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI.value: Sinclair, F.L., 1999. A general classification of agroforestry practice. Agroforestry systems, 46(2), pp.161-180.

value.value: An agroforestry practice based on trees, shrubs and perennial plants to create a carefully designed and maintained ecosystem of useful plants modelled on the structure of young natural woodland, utilising plants of direct and indirect benefit to people.

http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI.value: Crawford, Martin (2010). Creating a Forest Garden. Green Books. https://www.agroforestry.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/product/creating-a-forest-garden-2/Creating_a_forest_garden.pdf

value.value: A cropping system in which relatively short periods of cultivation are followed by relatively long periods of fallow.

http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI.value: FAO, 1982. University of Ibadan Workshop on Shifting Cultivation and Extension, in Ibadan. https://www.fao.org/3/r1340E/r1340e04.htm

value.value: Agroforestry practice in which grazing occurs in a forest area.

definition.value: An agricultural experiment during which at least two different crops are grown at the same time.

value.value: A environmental material which contains living microorganisms, which, when applied to seeds, plant surfaces, or soil, colonize the rhizosphere or the interior of the plant and promotes growth by increasing the supply or availability of primary nutrients to the host plant.
Charcoal used as a soil amendment.

definition.value: An animal manure composoed of the excrement of seabirds and bats.
A tillage process during which the tillage occurs at 25-30 cm depth. It can be used for deep rooted crop like pigeonpea.
Fish fertilizer is any fish product that is used specifically to feed plants and soil.
Process to remove unwanted plants from an area of ground.
Inorganic fertilizer that contains nitrogen
Inorganic fertilizer that contains phosphorus
Inorganic fertilizer that contains potassium
